eMOLT Weekly Update 2022-10-14

Weekly Recap

On Tuesday, Giovanni Gianesin and I went Chatham to install a few new instruments on the F/V Noah. Despite the pouring rain and howling wind, Captain Doug and crewman Tim worked with us to set up an RFID gear-in-gear-out system (to help make haul-by-haul fixed gear reporting easier for our Study Fleet partners) and an eMOLT dissolved oxygen / temperature system reporting via cell modem. Thanks to Nick Lowell for jumping online that afternoon to remotely smooth over a hiccup on the deckbox. Emma Fowler was able to get on board a few vessels including the F/V Nicole Leigh, which will soon be receiving a brand new eMOLT rig. Huanxin Xu programmed a new SD card for the F/V Virginia Marise so hopefully, one of us will be headed to Point Judith in the near future to get that system back online and fix any other issues that arise in the port between now and then.

On Wednesday, I met with Huanxin and Aubrey Ellertson from the Commercial Fisheries Research Foundation at the Bourne Public Library to go through some of our data quality control checks and talk about ways to improve fishermen’s ability to access the data they collect. As a reminder, if you are interested in being able to view your historic data, please check out the ODN data portal and request an account. Your detailed data will remain confidential and viewable only through that secure login.

On Thursday, there was a potluck lunch to celebrate JiM’s retirement at the Woods Hole Lab. A special thanks goes out to retired captain and eMOLT participant Dave Goethel of the F/V Ellen Diane, who made the trek all the way down from New Hampshire for the party. JiM’s colleagues shared a few stories of his willingness to listen to others, share his knowledge, and do what it takes to get good science done, and JiM received a clamming basket full of beer, coffee, and French pastries.

Realtime Summary (Vessels with Rockblock Satellite Transmitters)

Thanks to the relentless remnants of Hurricane Ian, this was a quiet week on the water.

This week, we received 24 haul-averaged reports from 6 vessels.

In the figure above, you can see the approximate locations where we receieved “Status Reports” (a ping from your system letting us know that it’s still working) and “Data Uploads” (actual temperature / depth data collected by your probes). The “Status Reports” come in every 12 hours or so when a system is powered up. “Data Uploads” only come in when you haul the probes.

One vessel that was out, the F/V Terri Ann returned some interesting results that show when Hurricane Fiona impacted their gear as it moved north towards the Maritimes around September 23rd-24th. You can see the pressure readings start to change rapidly as the storm system moves over the gear (gray line) followed by an increase in water temperature (red line).

Announcements and Upcoming Weeks

I mentioned before that I’m looking forward to meeting with many of you at the Maine Fishermen’s Forum next year, but there are other opportunities for commercial fishermen and scientists to get together before then.

  • The Cooperative Research Branch at the Northeast Fisheries Science Center is hosting two “Cooperative Research Summits” in early 2023 (January 31 in Newport News, VA and February 15 in Providence, RI) to highlight current coooperative research projects in the region and discuss opportunities for additional collaborations. There are stipends available to support fishermen attending. If you are interested, you can find more information here. Registration is online and closes on December 2, 2022.

  • Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution (in collaboration with the Northeast Fisheries Science Center, Gulf of Maine Lobster Foundation, Commercial Fisheries Research Foundation, and Ocean Data Networks) is hosting a three day workshop exploring the possibility of creating an eMOLT-style biogeochemical sensor array up and down the Eastern Seaboard using fishing gear to deploy sensors. The workshop will focus on gathering input from the fishing industry, instrument manufacturers, and data users and will take place in Falmouth, MA from January 18-20, 2023. Again, there are stipends available for fishing industry members to attend. If you are interested, please fill out the expression of interest form

If you’d like a hand registering for either event, have questions about them, or just want to introduce yourself please dont hesitate to reach out by email, text, or call.

All the best,

-George
